==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emery
<hw>Em"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧meri</ets>, earlier <ets>⟦eacute⟧meril</ets>, It.
<ets>smeriglio</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, <?/, <?/, cf. <?/ to wipe; perh. akin
to E. <ets>smear</ets>. Cf. <er>Emeril</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld>
<def>Corundum in the form of grains or powder, used in the arts for
grinding and polishing hard substances. Native emery is mixed with more
or less magnetic iron. See the Note under <er>Corundum</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Emery board</b></col>, <cd>cardboard pulp mixed with
emery and molded into convenient.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Emery
cloth</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Emery paper</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>cloth or paper on which the powder of emery is spread and glued for
scouring and polishing.</cd> -- <col><b>Emery wheel</b></col>, <cd>a
wheel containing emery, or having a surface of emery. In machine shops,
it is sometimes called a <altname>buff wheel</altname>, and by the
manufacturers of cutlery, a <altname>glazer</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

